\emph{How many steps} does it take to reach the exit?

\strong{Part Two}

Now, the jumps are even stranger: after each jump, if the offset was
\emph{three or more}, instead \emph{decrease} it by \code{1}. Otherwise, increase it by
\code{1} as before.

Using this rule with the above example, the process now takes \code{10}
steps, and the offset values after finding the exit are left as
\code{2 3 2 3 -1}.

\emph{How many steps} does it now take to reach the exit?
